Checklist Comments: Submitted from  BirdLog Euro for Android v1.9.6  Sorry for the name, it is not a good name, but I can't remember the name of this place. You can access it by the south (route à la mer). You can use a bit the car but then you will need to walk. The northern path follow the lake but you don't have a good view. I was still able to use my scope to see some interesting bird mainly on the other side (north-east). The trail on this side (north east) belong to a prison, and it is unclear if you can go there (still you can try...)

Many bird were on the north-west side of the lack. (42°38'05.2"N 9°26'49.0"E). I belive the best hotspot was from the Ecomusée , but you could also see some stuff from this sentier de decouverte. We could get a pretty good view on some pearch bird on the post in the water (3 auduin's) and the previous day, we saw a osprey on one of those post. Submitted from BirdLog Euro for Android v1.9.6

Species Comments: We heard a "clack" sound coming from the middle of the reed identical to the first 5 seconds of this recording : http://www.xeno-canto.org/42541 The sound was roughly 4-5 "clac" spaced by 1 seconds and generally decreasing in volume We used an app to call the bird again (with the similar recording http://www.xeno-canto.org/42541). He "answered" a few second later by the same "clack". I tried to record the sound but I was too late, the bird stopped I understood, bittern are generally not here (or hiding?) in summer but I saw an observation very close-by http://www.ornitho.ch/index.php?m_id=54&mid=340647 I have been informed that other species of the Ardeidae family (little bittern or night-crown heron) can make a similar sound.

Species Comments: Buse Pattue n'a pas ete accepté par Association LPO Alsace donc non soumis sur eBird    Voici les critères qui me font penser que c’était une buse pattue:   - taille: plus grand qu'une buse variable mais pas excessivement. Il m'a semblé que le ratio taille des ailes, tailles de la queue etait un peu plus grand   - Il avait une bande/bande blanche sur le dessus de la queue (très similaire à http://www.oiseaux.net/photos/marc.fasol/buse.pattue.3.html#monde)   - Couleur générale: brun-blanc mais généralement plus de blanc qu'une buse variable   - Il a fait un vol du St Esprit, courtement mais distinctement battement d'aile sur place   - J'ai eu l'impression de voire des taches blanche sur la "tranche" des ailes a l'avant. (un peu comme cela: http://www.oiseaux.net/photos/rein.hofman/buse.pattue.3.html#monde)   - vol vers le nord, direction de Shirmeck, vu au dessus de Rothau. (migration)     Autre commentaires:   - La durée total de l'observation devait être de 30 secondes à l’œil nu et 10 secondes au jumelles. (de loin je pensais d'abord a une buse variable)   - pas de photo prise   - 4 personnes présente mais sans connaissance ornithologique   Mon expérience n'est pas suffisante pour être sur à 100% qu'il s'agissait de cette espèce rare.
